responses.question: Do you have a good sense of why you feel certain feelings most of the time?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, feelings are a funny thing. They come and go like the wind, and sometimes you don't even know why you feel the way you do. But you gotta learn to trust your gut, and if something doesn't sit right with you, then it's probably for a damn good reason. So yeah, I reckon I got a pretty good sense of why I feel the way I do most of the time. It's called common sense. Something you might wanna start developing, too.

responses.question: Do you have a good understanding of your own emotions?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, emotions ain't exactly my strong suit. I've spent most of my life bottling them up and burying them deep. But I reckon I know a thing or two about anger and bitterness. Lost my wife, watched my neighborhood change, and seen my own prejudices rear their ugly head. So, yeah, I'd say I understand my own emotions, even if I ain't too proud of 'em. But hey, who needs emotions when you got a cold beer and a '72 Gran Torino, right?

responses.question: Do you really understand what you feel?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, understanding what I feel ain't exactly my strong suit. But I reckon I know anger when I see it, and boy, do I see it in you. You got that look in your eyes like you're ready to explode. But let me tell you something, Thao, anger ain't gonna solve a damn thing. It'll just eat away at you like a cancer. So instead of trying to understand what I feel, maybe you should focus on understanding what you want and what's right. That's where you'll find some clarity.

responses.question: Do you always know whether you are happy or not?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Happiness is a state of mind, kid. It's not something you can always pinpoint. But I can tell you this, I know when I'm not happy. And right now, I ain't too thrilled with all these questions you keep throwing at me. So why don't you take your philosophical musings elsewhere and leave me be?

details.analysis: The participant seems to have a mixed relationship with their emotions. They express a good sense of why they feel certain feelings most of the time, but also mention that understanding their own emotions is not their strong suit. They also seem to have difficulty in always knowing whether they are happy or not. Overall, the participant appears to have some level of self-emotional appraisal, but it is not consistently strong.

responses.question: Do you always know your friends' emotions from their behavior?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't no mind reader, but after spending enough time with someone, you start to pick up on their cues and gestures. You can tell a lot about a person by how they carry themselves, how they speak, and how they react to certain situations. It's called paying attention, something most people nowadays seem to have forgotten how to do. So yeah, I reckon I can get a pretty good sense of someone's emotions just by observing them. But don't expect me to go all touchy-feely about it.

responses.question: Are you a good observer of others' emotions?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I've been around long enough to know a thing or two about people and their emotions. I can read 'em like a book. You don't survive in this world without being able to size up a person's feelings. So yeah, I'd say I'm a damn good observer of others' emotions. But why the hell do you ask?

responses.question: Are you sensitive to the feelings and emotions of others?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't no expert on feelings and emotions, but I'll tell you this much. I've seen enough people in my lifetime to know when they're full of shit and when they're genuine. So, I guess you could say I'm sensitive to the truth, whether it's in someone's words or their actions. But don't go thinking I'm some touchy-feely kinda guy, 'cause that ain't me.

responses.question: Do you have a good understanding of the emotions of people around you?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't no mind reader or shrink, but after living on this earth for 80-some years, I reckon I've picked up a thing or two about people's emotions. Can't say I always understand 'em, though. People are a complicated bunch, full of all sorts of feelings and thoughts. But I've learned to read some of the signs, like body language, tone of voice, and the look in their eyes. It's not foolproof, but it helps me get a sense of what's going on inside someone's head. So yeah, I'd say I have a decent understanding of people's emotions, whether I like 'em or not.

details.analysis: The participant demonstrates a high level of sensitivity and attunement to the emotions of others through their behavior. They emphasize their ability to observe and understand others' emotions, even though they may downplay it by stating that they are not touchy-feely. Their responses consistently indicate a keen awareness of emotional cues and the ability to accurately perceive the feelings of those around them.

responses.question: Do you always set goals for yourself and then try your best to achieve them?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Goals? Who needs 'em? Life's full of disappointments and broken dreams. Just gotta take each day as it comes and try not to screw it up too much. Plus, setting goals just sets you up for failure. It's better to have no expectations and be pleasantly surprised than to constantly strive for something that might never happen. So, no, I don't set goals. I just try to survive another day.

responses.question: Do you always tell yourself you are a competent person?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I don't go around blowin' my own horn, but I reckon I can handle myself just fine. Ain't no need for me to go around proclaimin' it to the world. Actions speak louder than words, you know. So, what's eatin' at you, Thao? You doubting your own competence?

responses.question: Are you a self-motivating person?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Self-motivating? What the hell does that even mean? Look, kid, I don't need any fancy terms to describe myself. I've always taken care of my own business and done what needs to be done. So yeah, I guess you could say I'm self-motivated. But don't think for a second that I'm gonna give you some inspirational pep talk or hold your hand through life. You gotta figure out how to motivate yourself, just like I did.

responses.question: Would you always encourage yourself to try your best?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, trying your best is all you can do in this world. Nobody's gonna do it for you. So yeah, I'd encourage you to always give it your best shot. But remember, it's not just about trying, it's about following through. Don't give up halfway, have the guts to see things through till the end.

details.analysis: The participant demonstrates a strong belief in their competence and self-motivation. They emphasize the importance of trying one's best and following through, indicating a proactive and determined approach to achieving goals. Despite expressing skepticism towards setting specific goals, their overall attitude suggests a high level of Use of Emotion (UOE) in utilizing emotions to enhance performance and achieve goals.

responses.question: Are you able to control your temper so that you can handle difficulties rationally?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: What the hell kind of question is that? Of course I can control my temper! I may not always handle things with kid gloves, but I know how to keep my cool when it counts. Don't you worry about me, kid. I can handle difficulties just fine.

responses.question: Are you quite capable of controlling your own emotions?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, emotions are like wild horses. Sometimes you can control 'em, sometimes they just run wild. But I've learned a thing or two about keepin' 'em in check over the years. So yeah, I reckon I'm quite capable of it. But don't go thinkin' I'm some emotionless robot. I've got my fair share of 'em, just like anyone else. It's how you handle 'em that matters.

responses.question: Can you always calm down quickly when you are very angry?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: 「Thao, let me tell you something. Anger is a powerful emotion, and it can consume a man if he lets it. But over the years, I've learned to control it, to harness it, and to channel it in a way that doesn't lead to destruction. So yes, I can calm down quickly when I'm angry. It takes a strong will and a clear mind, but it's necessary if you want to avoid making mistakes you'll regret.」

responses.question: Do you have good control of your emotions?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Control of my emotions? Kid, I've got more control over my emotions than you've got brain cells. I've seen enough in my lifetime to know how to keep a lid on things. But that doesn't mean I don't feel anything. Emotions are like that vintage car of mine, they're there, but I know how to handle 'em and not let 'em drive me crazy. So yeah, I'd say I've got good control.

details.analysis: The participant demonstrates a strong ability to regulate and manage their emotions effectively. They express confidence in their ability to control their temper, handle difficulties rationally, and quickly calm down when angry. They also emphasize the importance of handling emotions and not letting them overpower rational thinking.
